\title{closure of [surjections](jms-00M8) under [identity](jms-00II) and [composition](jms-00IN)}
\date{2024-01-29}
\author{jonmsterling}
\contributor{marcelofiore}
\taxon{theorem}
\import{jms-00JB}

\p{The [identity function](jms-00KI) is a [surjection](jms-00M8) and the [composition](jms-00IN) of [surjections](jms-00M8) yields a [surjection](jms-00M8).}

\proof{
 \p{For the [identity function](jms-00KI) on a set #{A}, we must check that for all #{a\in A}, there exists an element #{a'\in A} such that #{a'=a}. Of course, we choose #{a' := a}.}

 \p{Let #{f\colon A\twoheadrightarrow B} and #{g\colon B\twoheadrightarrow C} be two [surjections](jms-00M8). To show that #{g\circ f\colon A\to C} is a [surjection](jms-00M8), we fix #{c\in C} to exhibit some #{a\in A} such that #{g\prn{f\prn{a}} = c}. Because #{g\colon B\twoheadrightarrow C} is [surjective](jms-00M8), there exists #{b\in B} such that #{g\prn{b} = c}. Becuase #{f\colon A\twoheadrightarrow B} is [surjective](jms-00M8), there exists #{a\in A} such that #{f\prn{a} = b}. Thus we have #{g\prn{f\prn{a}}=g\prn{b}=c}.}
}